<section>
  <p>I first got hooked on electric skateboards after riding my friend, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/user/sampsheffer">Sam Sheffer’s</a>, <a href="https://boostedboards.com/">Boosted Board</a> around the East Village in New York City. The feeling of surfing along pavement is exhilarating, I had to have an electric skateboard but I wanted that connection you only get when you build one yourself. After a fair amount of research I stumbled across <a href="http://runplayback.com/i-built-another-diy-electric-longboard-with-more-power">Rik Cordero’s build</a> and decided to make something similar. Soon, working with the board became my focus in my free time as I dug into how electronic speed controllers worked, battery voltage and amperage limits, and different ways to drive <acronym title="direct current">DC</acronym> motors.</p>
  <p>This process of doing it myself is something that has been part of projects since I was a kid. If I wanted a computer, ok, go out and find parts and put them together. If I wanted a go kart, ok, find parts and put them together. Every project came with unique challenges and pitfalls but I’ve always learned so much in the process of overcoming them. If I were to ever second guess a feature of something I built I can always get in there and fix or improve the project.</p>
  <p>I started the project with a Thriller downhill 38.3" deck from <a href="http://www.jetskateboards.com/">JET Skateboards</a>, <a href="http://www.carvonskates.com/">CarvOn</a> v2 hub motors, <acronym title="44.4 Volt">12s</acronym> <a href="http://diyelectricskateboard.com/">Torqueboards</a> <acronym title="electronic speed controller">ESC</acronym>s, and a <acronym title="10 serial, 4 parallel cells">10s4p</acronym> battery from Enertion. After burning up the <acronym title="electronic speed controller">ESC</acronym>s I opted for <a href="http://www.ollinboardcompany.com/">Ollin</a> <acronym title="Vedder’s electronic speec controller">VESC</acronym>s which allow much more control over how the motors are driven as they are open source and easily programmable. This change allowed me to put the run in <acronym title="field-oriented control">FOC</acronym> mode for a much smoother and quieter motor operation.</p>
